    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1967-05-14T22:38:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1967-05-14T22:38:00-05:00" n="355"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d355">
                <head>355. Telegram From <gloss type="from">the Mission to the European Office of
                        the United Nations</gloss> to <gloss type="to">the Department of
                        State</gloss>
                    <note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d355fn1">Source: Department of State, Central
                        Files, FT 13–2 US. Confidential; Flash; Limdis-Potatoes. Received on May 15
                        at 12:13 a.m. and passed to the White House.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Geneva</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1967-05-15T03:38:00+00:00">May 15, 1967, 0338Z</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>3663. For <persName corresp="#p_BFM1">Bator</persName> from <persName
                        corresp="#p_RWM2">Roth</persName>.</p>
                <list>
                    <label>1.</label>
                    <item>This will be a brief report before going to bed.</item>
                    <label>2.</label>
                    <item>As of 3:30, Japanese bilaterals still going on in Mission and grains
                        discussions endlessly bickering in Bocage over basing points. Everything
                        else on grains except Japanese food aid settled.</item>
                    <label>3.</label>
                    <item>After impossible bilateral with <persName corresp="#p_RJ8">Rey</persName>
                        and Hijzen at 10:00 and subsequent <persName corresp="#p_RJ8">Rey</persName>
                        discussion with <persName corresp="#p_WWE1">Wyndham White</persName>, it was
                        apparent that no further movement in key chemical section was available.
                        Mike and I had several talks with <persName corresp="#p_WWE1">Wyndham
                            White</persName> and persuaded him not to stop the clock as this would
                        merely allow the negotiators to go to bed.</item>
                    <label>4.</label>
                    <item>Finally, we decided that the only way to break the impasse was to give
                            <persName corresp="#p_WWE1">Wyndham White</persName> a compromise
                        decoupage package and then to persuade him to issue it as his own
                        suggestion.</item>
                    <label>5.</label>
                    <item>
                        <p>We therefore made the following proposal:</p>
                        <p>For chemical products in BTN Chapters 28–39 <pb facs="0959" n="929"
                                xml:id="pg_929"/>
                            <list>
                                <label>A.</label>
                                <item>Firm <gloss target="#t_KR1">KR</gloss> commitment <list>
                                        <label>1.</label>
                                        <item>
                                            <gloss target="#t_EEC1">EEC</gloss> cuts 20 percent
                                            generally. 30 percent on rates 25 percent ave and over.
                                            35 percent on Swiss annex items.</item>
                                        <label>2.</label>
                                        <item>
                                            <gloss target="#t_UK1">UK</gloss> cuts 20 percent
                                            generally. 30 percent on rates 25 percent ave and
                                            over.</item>
                                        <label>3.</label>
                                        <item>US cuts 50 percent generally. 20 percent on rates 8
                                            percent ave and under.</item>
                                        <label>4.</label>
                                        <item>Japan, Switzerland, and all others commit full offer
                                            in <gloss target="#t_KR1">KR</gloss>.</item>
                                    </list>
                                </item>
                                <label>B.</label>
                                <item>Conditional package <list>
                                        <label>1.</label>
                                        <item>
                                            <gloss target="#t_EEC1">EEC</gloss>, <gloss
                                                target="#t_UK1">UK</gloss>, and Switzerland make
                                            additional commitment on <gloss target="#t_NTB1"
                                                >NTB</gloss> or other appropriate concession.</item>
                                        <label>2.</label>
                                        <item>US converts <gloss target="#t_ASP1">ASP</gloss> and
                                            lowers rates where indicated to general level of 20
                                            percent.</item>
                                        <label>3.</label>
                                        <item>
                                            <gloss target="#t_EEC1">EEC</gloss> and <gloss
                                                target="#t_UK1">UK</gloss> make remaining cuts to 50
                                            percent overall reductions;<gloss target="#t_UK1"
                                                >UK</gloss> cuts 33–1/3 percent rates to 12–1/2
                                            percent.</item>
                                    </list>
                                </item>
                            </list>
                        </p>
                    </item>
                    <label>6.</label>
                    <item>The approximate consequence of the above formula is a U.S. overall cut of
                        somewhere between 42 and 43 percent against a combined <gloss
                            target="#t_EEC1">EEC</gloss>-Japan-<gloss target="#t_UK1">UK</gloss> cut
                        of somewhere between 25 and 30 percent. Given the confusion of the formula
                        and a certain European logic the figures do not come out too badly.
                        Obviously the Community will in the first instance reject it, but at least
                        we will now have a Secretariat recommendation that is acceptable to
                        us.</item>
                    <label>7.</label>
                    <item>We now plan to call a meeting of the heads of delegations of the <gloss
                            target="#t_EEC1">EEC</gloss>, <gloss target="#t_UK1">UK</gloss>, Japan,
                        and U.S. for 11 o’clock tomorrow. We have a little more time left, but not
                        very much as this situation can begin to unravel very quickly.</item>
                    <label>8.</label>
                    <item>don’t worry, we will not let this unravelling happen, but we must push as
                        far as possible in an effort to avoid putting the President in a most
                        difficult domestic situation.</item>
                    <label>9.</label>
                    <item>We are still in deep negotiations with the Japanese and bickering with the
                        British. I am sure our problems with the latter can be solved, and
                        ultimately the Japanese must come along if all other pieces fall
                        together.</item>
                </list>
                <p>Goodnight Potatoes.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName>
                            <hi rend="strong">Tubby</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
